#import "../book.typ": *
// ===================== ANA B’KOACH =====================
#startprayer("Ana B’koach", "אָנָּא בְּכֹחַ")
#stanza("Ána b’kóach g’dulát y’minchá tatir tz’rurá.",
  "אָנָּא בְּכֹחַ גְּדֻלַּת יְמִינְךָ תַּתִּיר צְרוּרָה.")
#stanza("Kabél rinát amchá, sagvénu, tahárenu, norá.",
  "קַבֵּל רִנַּת עַמְּךָ שַׂגְּבֵנוּ טַהֲרֵנוּ נוֹרָא.")
#stanza("Na gibór, dorshéi yichudchá k’vavát shomrém.",
  "נָא גִבּוֹר דּוֹרְשֵׁי יִחוּדְךָ כְּבָבַת שָׁמְרֵם.")
#stanza("Barchém, tahárem, rachamém, tzidkatchá tamíd gomlém.",
  "בָּרְכֵם טַהֲרֵם רַחֲמֵם צִדְקָתְךָ תָּמִיד גָּמְלֵם.")
#stanza("Chasín kadósh, b’rov tuvchá nahél adatécha.",
  "חֲסִין קָדוֹשׁ בְּרֹב טוּבְךָ נַהֵל עֲדָתֶךָ.")
#stanza("Yachíd ge’é, l’amchá p’né, zochréi k’dushatécha.",
  "יָחִיד גֵּאֶה לְעַמְּךָ פְּנֵה, זוֹכְרֵי קְדֻשָּׁתֶךָ.")
#stanza("Shav’aténu kabél ushmá tza’akaténu, yodé’a ta’alumót.",
  "שַׁוְעָתֵנוּ קַבֵּל וּשְׁמַע צַעֲקָתֵנוּ יוֹדֵעַ תַּעֲלוּמוֹת.")
#rubric([said softly, as after the Sh’ma])
#stanza("Barúch shem k’vod malchutó l’olám va’éd.",
  "בָּרוּךְ שֵׁם כְּבוֹד מַלְכוּתוֹ לְעוֹלָם וָעֶד.")
#eng("Please — by the great strength of Your right hand, set the bound ones free.")
#eng("Receive the glad song of Your people; lift us, purify us, awesome One.")
#eng("Please, Mighty One — guard those who seek Your oneness like the pupil of an eye.")
#eng("Bless them, purify them, show them compassion; let Your justice always be their reward.")
#eng("Mighty and holy One, in Your abundant goodness, guide Your community.")
#eng("You who are one and exalted, turn toward Your people — those who call Your holiness to mind.")
#eng("Accept our cry and hear our plea, You who know all that is hidden.")
#engn("Blessed is the name of Your glorious majesty forever and ever.",
  [Seven lines of six words each hide, in their opening letters, the mystical forty-two-letter Name
  of God — a prayer folded quietly inside a prayer. Tradition assigns it to the first-century sage
  Nechunya ben HaKanah, but scholars read that as legend and the poem itself as most likely medieval;
  the reaching-out is no less real for that.])
